Mockups are dangerous because they are static. In a design tool, everything is perfect. The data is exactly the right length, the user always follows the intended path, and the network never fails. 

But the moment you move that design onto a real device, the mirror reflects a much harsher reality. 

### Truth in Motion

The first thing the screen tells you is that your animations are too slow. In your head, that transition was "elegant." On the device, it feels like an obstacle. You realize that the user doesn't want to watch your clever code; they want to get their work done.

This is the "Stranger Test" again. The device is a neutral observer. It shows you the friction you were too close to see. It shows you that the button you thought was accessible is actually too small for a thumb in a hurry.

### The Pedagogy of the Bug

We often think of bugs as mistakes, but they are actually lessons. A bug is the computer telling you: **"You didn't think about this."** 

When I was building the recording flow for my heartbeat app, I had a perfect mental model of how the audio would save. But the first time I ran it on a real device, it crashed. Why? Because I hadn't considered what happens if a user gets a phone call in the middle of a session.

That crash forced me to learn about `AVAudioSession` interruptionsâ€”something I never would have researched if I had just stayed in the "idea phase." 

### Beyond the Mockup

I've learned to stop spending weeks in design tools. Now, I try to get a prototype on the screen as fast as possible. 

The screen is where the narrative of your app actually begins. It's where you stop talking about what the app *could* be and start dealing with what it *is*. It forces you to be honest. It forces you to be precise. 

And most importantly, it forces you to be helpful. A beautiful mockup can win an award, but only a functioning, battle-tested app can solve a problem.
